\begin_layout Subsubsection
Michelson interferometer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Directly measuring the phase of light is difficult so one has to resort
 to interferometry techniques.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.1.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Danilishin2012"

\end_inset

: quick summary with trick to improve sensitivity: introduction of some
 constant small bias 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L_{0}$
\end_inset

 between the arms lengths.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Fabry-Perot Interferometer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Intro
\emph default
:
\emph on
 
\emph default
^
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The Michelson interferometer is useful in analyzing the coherence function
 or power spectrum of light sources with coherence lengths of the order
 of centimeters or less.
 The analysis of light sources with longer coherence lengths is not feasible
 with the Michelson interferometer ...
 because of the length of the arms required.
 On the other hand, if one could allow light to bounce back and forth many
 times within an arm, one would increase the effective path length while
 reducing the size of the instrument.
 ...
 The device, which consists of two partially transmitting surfaces facing
 each other, operates on the principle of multiple beam interference.
 Light which enters the instrument from one side is reﬂected back and forth
 many times , with a little light escaping at each interface.
 The light which leaves is the superposition of all the partial beams which
 emerge from the partially transmitting output mirror.
 ...
 If the separation between the plates, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, is constant one speaks of a 
\emph on
Fabry-Perot etalon
\emph default
, otherwise it is called a 
\emph on
Fabry-Perot interferometer
\emph default
.
 Because of the long effective path length inside the interferometer, the
 surfaces of the partially transmitting mirrors must be made with great
 precision so as to not cause phase distortion in the light beam which is
 being analyzed.
 A high quality Fabry-Perot interferometer can have a surface ﬂatness of
 better than λ/100.
 In addition, the mirror surfaces may be curved (in particular, convex)
 so that the light during its many traversals is conﬁned to the cavity.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vanDrielO"

\end_inset

 section 7.6.2)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\emph on
Description
\emph default
: 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fabry perot analysis.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:fabry perot driel"

\end_inset

From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vanDrielO"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will assume that the Fabry-Perot instrument is symmetric: i.e.
 both partial mirros are identical and so have the same the same reflectivity
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\equiv re^{i\phi}$
\end_inset

 and the same transmissivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi\equiv te^{i\sigma}$
\end_inset

.
 As illustrated in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:fabry perot driel"

\end_inset

, a continuous light beam of amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{0}$
\end_inset

 reaches the cavity at an angle of incidence (i.e.
 the angle between the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and the normal to the mirrors) 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 For a non-attenuating medium, we obtain that the intensity being transmitted
 from the cavity is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
I_{out} & = & \frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}\label{eq:fabry transmitted intensity}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=2\phi+\delta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=2\omega nd\cos\theta/c$
\end_inset

 is the phase difference between beams following 2 successive reflections
 inside the cavity and the functional form of the above equation is known
 as the 
\emph on
Airy function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F & = & \frac{\pi\sqrt{R}}{1-R}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

is called the 
\emph on
finesse 
\emph default
of the interferometer and 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\left|\Gamma\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the reflection coefficient*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The phase difference between beams following 2 successive reflections inside
 the cavity is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\delta & = & 2kd\cos\theta=2\frac{2\pi n}{\lambda_{0}}d\cos\theta
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 because see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:path differences fabry perot"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename derivation path difference fabry perot.png

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:path differences fabry perot"

\end_inset

Clarification on the path difference expression: The path difference is
 given by =
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta l & = & \left(\xi_{3}+\xi_{1}+\xi_{2}+\xi_{2}\right)-\left(\xi_{3}+\xi_{1}+\xi_{3}\right)\\
 & = & 2\xi_{2}-\xi_{3}=\left(2\xi_{1}+2\xi_{3}\right)-\xi_{3}=2\xi_{1}+\xi_{3}\\
 & = & \xi_{1}+\left(\xi_{1}+\xi_{3}\right)=\xi_{1}+\xi_{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Now, the total electric field exiting the cavity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathcal{E} & = & \mbox{First transmitted beam+Second transmitted beam+....}\\
 & = & \mbox{Beam that goes through both mirrors+}\\
 &  & \mbox{Beam that goes through 1st mirror then reflected twice then transmitted through mirror 2 and accumulates}\\
 &  & \mbox{a phase shift+...}\\
 & = & \mathcal{E}_{0}\Phi^{2}+\mathcal{E}_{0}\Phi^{2}\Gamma^{2}e^{i\delta}+\mathcal{E}_{0}\Phi^{2}\Gamma^{2}e^{2i\delta}+...\\
 & = & \mathcal{E}_{0}\Phi^{2}\left(1+\Gamma^{2}e^{i\delta}+\Gamma^{4}e^{2i\delta}+...\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is a geometric series because 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Gamma\right|^{2}\leq1$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathcal{E} & = & \mathcal{E}_{0}\Phi^{2}\frac{1}{1-\Gamma^{2}e^{i\delta}}\\
\implies I & \propto & \left|\mathcal{E}\right|^{2}\\
I & = & \frac{I_{0}\left|\Phi\right|^{4}}{\left|1-\Gamma^{2}e^{i\delta}\right|^{2}}\\
 & = & \frac{I_{0}T^{2}}{\left|1-r^{2}e^{i\Delta}\right|^{2}}=\frac{I_{0}T^{2}}{\left(1+R^{2}-2R\cos\Delta\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{I_{0}T^{2}}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}/\left(\frac{1+R^{2}}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}-\frac{2R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}\cos\Delta\right)\\
 & = & \frac{I_{0}T^{2}}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}/\left(\frac{1+R^{2}}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}-\frac{2R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}\left(1-2\sin^{2}\frac{\Delta}{2}\right)\right)\\
 & = & \frac{I_{0}T^{2}}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}/\left(1+\frac{4R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}\sin^{2}\frac{\Delta}{2}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

For a non-attenuating medium we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $T=1-R$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I & = & \frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{out}/I_{0}$
\end_inset

 is plotted for different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fabry airy function.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vanDrielO"

\end_inset

; TODO: Redo with Mathematica
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 From Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fabry transmitted intensity"

\end_inset

, we notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{out}$
\end_inset

 is at a maximum for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=2m\pi$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 (this defines the resonance condition), each of which corresponds to a
 resonant frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{m}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta/2 & = & \omega_{m}nd\cos\theta/c+\phi.\label{eq:fabry parameter}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Moreover, the intensity being reflected from the cavity is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I_{r} & = & I_{0}\frac{4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph on
Calculating power
\emph default
 
\emph on
exiting to the left
\emph default
: By conservation of energy we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{out}+I_{r}=I_{in}=I_{0},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{out}$
\end_inset

 is the power leaving the cavity to the right (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fabry transmitted intensity"

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{r}$
\end_inset

 is the power reflected to the left of the first mirror.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(Note that we have ignored the power stored in the cavity because we are
 working in the steady state regime: as the cavity reaches steady state,
 energy is built up inside the cavity) Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{r}=I_{0}-I_{out}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I_{r} & = & I_{0}-I_{out}=I_{0}-\frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}\\
 & = & I_{0}\frac{4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(Alternate brute force derivation which shows that you have to be careful
 with the reciprocity relations):*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The path difference (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:path differences fabry perot"

\end_inset

) between two successive transmitted beams to the left (i.e.
 back to the input port) is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta l & = & \left(\xi_{3}+\xi_{1}+\xi_{2}\right)-\left(\xi_{3}\right)\\
 & = & \xi_{1}+\xi_{2}=2d\cos\theta
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Denote the phase difference by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=2kd\cos\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Then, the total electric field exiting the cavity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathcal{E} & = & \mbox{First transmitted beam+Second transmitted beam+....}\\
 & = & \mbox{Beam that is directly reflected+}\\
 &  & \mbox{Beam that goes through 1st mirror then reflected then transmitted through mirror 1 and accumulates}\\
 &  & \mbox{a phase shift+...}\\
 & = & -\mathcal{E}_{0}\Gamma^{*}+\mathcal{E}_{0}\left|\Phi\right|^{2}\Gamma e^{i\delta}+\mathcal{E}_{0}\left|\Phi\right|^{2}\Gamma^{3}e^{2i\delta}+...\\
 & = & -\mathcal{E}_{0}\Gamma^{*}+\mathcal{E}_{0}T\Gamma e^{i\delta}\left(1+\Gamma^{2}e^{i\delta}+\Gamma^{4}e^{2i\delta}+...\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the first term contains 
\begin_inset Formula $-\Gamma^{*}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

, and the second term 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Phi\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi^{2}$
\end_inset

 because of the reciprocity relations*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The reciprocity relations (Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:stokesReciprocityRelations"

\end_inset

) have to be satisfied: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Gamma^{*}\Phi^{'}+\Gamma^{'*}\Phi^{'} & = & 0,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi^{'}$
\end_inset

 is the transmissivity for electric field crossing the mirror from right
 to left and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{'}$
\end_inset

 is the reflectivity for electric incident (from right to left) to the right
 side of the side of the first mirror.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Then we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Phi^{'} & = & \Phi^{*}\left(\frac{-\Gamma^{'}}{\Gamma^{*}}\right).\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{'}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{'}=-\Gamma^{*}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Phi^{'} & = & \Phi^{*}\\
\implies\Phi^{'}\Phi & = & \left|\Phi\right|^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the second is a geometric series because 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Gamma\right|^{2}\leq1$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathcal{E} & = & -\mathcal{E}_{0}\Gamma^{*}+\mathcal{E}_{0}T\Gamma e^{i\delta}\left(\frac{1}{1-\Gamma^{2}e^{i\delta}}\right)=-\mathcal{E}_{0}\Gamma e^{-2i\phi}+\mathcal{E}_{0}T\Gamma e^{i\delta}\left(\frac{1}{1-\Gamma^{2}e^{i\delta}}\right)\\
 & = & \mathcal{E}_{0}\Gamma\frac{e^{i\delta}\left(T+\Gamma^{2}e^{-2i\phi}\right)-e^{-2i\phi}}{1-\Gamma^{2}e^{i\delta}}=\mathcal{E}_{0}\Gamma\frac{e^{i\delta}\left(T+R\right)-e^{-2i\phi}}{1-\Gamma^{2}e^{i\delta}}\\
I & \propto & \left|\mathcal{E}\right|^{2}\\
\implies I & = & I_{0}\left|\Gamma\right|^{2}\frac{\left|-e^{-2i\phi}+e^{i\delta}\left(T+R\right)\right|^{2}}{\left|1-\Gamma^{2}e^{i\delta}\right|^{2}}\\
 & = & I_{0}R\frac{1+\left|T+R\right|^{2}-2\re{e^{i\left(\delta+2\phi\right)}\left(T+R\right)}}{\left|1-r^{2}e^{i\Delta}\right|^{2}}\\
 & = & I_{0}R\frac{1+T^{2}+R^{2}+2RT-2\left(T+R\right)\cos\left(\delta+2\phi\right)}{\left(1+R^{2}-2R\cos\Delta\right)}\\
 & = & \left[\frac{I_{0}R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}/\left(\frac{1+R^{2}}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}-\frac{2R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}\cos\Delta\right)\right]\left(1+\left(T+R\right)^{2}-2\left(T+R\right)\cos\left(\delta+2\phi\right)\right)\\
 & = & \left[\frac{I_{0}R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}/\left(\frac{1+R^{2}}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}-\frac{2R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}\left(1-2\sin^{2}\frac{\Delta}{2}\right)\right)\right]\left(1+\left(T+R\right)^{2}-2\left(T+R\right)\cos\left(\delta+2\phi\right)\right)\\
 & = & \left[\frac{I_{0}R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}/\left(1+\frac{4R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}\sin^{2}\frac{\Delta}{2}\right)\right]\left(1+\left(T+R\right)^{2}-2\left(T+R\right)\cos\left(\delta+2\phi\right)\right)\\
 & = & \left[\frac{I_{0}R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}/\left(1+\frac{4R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}\sin^{2}\frac{\Delta}{2}\right)\right]\left(1+\left(T+R\right)^{2}-2\left(T+R\right)\cos\left(\delta+2\phi\right)\right)\\
 & = & \frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}\frac{R}{\left(1-R\right)^{2}}\left(1+\left(T+R\right)^{2}-2\left(T+R\right)\cos\left(\delta+2\phi\right)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Assuming a non-attenuating medium (
\begin_inset Formula $T=1-R$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $T+R=1$
\end_inset

), and using that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\delta+2\phi$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I & = & \frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}\frac{R}{T^{2}}\left(2-2\cos\left(\Delta\right)\right)\\
 & = & \frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}\frac{R}{T^{2}}2\left(1-\cos\left(\Delta\right)\right)\\
 & = & \frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\frac{\Delta}{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where in the last equality we have used that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\cos\Delta & = & 1-2\sin^{2}\frac{\Delta}{2}\\
\implies\sin^{2}\frac{\Delta}{2} & = & \frac{1-\cos\Delta}{2}\\
\implies\left(1-\cos\Delta\right) & = & 2\sin^{2}\frac{\Delta}{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F & = & \frac{\pi\sqrt{R}}{1-R}\\
\implies\left(F/\pi\right)^{2} & = & \frac{R}{T^{2}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The constant frequency separation between different resonances is called
 the 
\emph on
free spectral range
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
FSR & = & \omega_{m+1}-\omega_{m}=\frac{\pi c}{nd\cos\theta}\\
 & = & \frac{2\pi}{\tau_{RT}},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{RT}$
\end_inset

 is the time light takes to make a roundtrip inside the cavity*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tau_{RT} & = & \frac{\mbox{distance}}{\mbox{speed}}=\frac{2d\cos\theta}{c/n}\\
 & = & 2\times\frac{nd\cos\theta}{c\pi}\times\pi=\frac{2\pi}{FSR}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Denote the FWHM of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{out}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Then, assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

 and a high reflection coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta\omega & \approx & \frac{FSR}{F}\qquad\left(R\approx1\right).\label{eq:approx FWHM of Iout Fabry}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 denote the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 at which we reach the FWHM
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{1}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)} & = & \frac{1}{2}\\
\implies4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right) & = & 1\\
\implies\sin\Delta/2 & = & \frac{\pi}{2F}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

If we have a high reflectivity then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\approx\epsilon+2m\pi$
\end_inset

 and so we can write - denoting the frequency when 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{out}$
\end_inset

 reaches 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}/2$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1/2}$
\end_inset

- that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta & \approx & \frac{\pi}{F}\\
\Delta & = & 2\frac{\omega_{1/2}n}{c}d\cos\theta+2\phi\\
\implies\omega_{1/2} & = & \frac{\left(\Delta-2\phi\right)c}{2nd\cos\theta}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Denote the FWHM of the frequency by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega_{1/2}$
\end_inset

 then assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta\omega_{1/2} & = & 2\left(\frac{\Delta c}{2nd\cos\theta}\right)\\
 & = & \Delta\frac{1}{\pi}\times FSR\\
 & = & \frac{FSR}{F}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vanDrielO"

\end_inset

 section 7.6.2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Resolving power of the Fabry-Perot
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 2 waves of slightly different frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{'}$
\end_inset

 falling on the interferometer then if we assume that the two sources are
 mutually incoherent (i.e.
 no interference effects between them) and that they have the same intensity
 then the overall transmitted intensity is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I_{out} & = & \frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}+\frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta^{'}/2\right)},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=2\omega nd\cos\theta/c+2\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{'}=2\omega^{'}nd\cos\theta/c+2\phi$
\end_inset

.
 In order to say that we can resolve the lines in the intensity pattern
 we must adopt a suitable criterion.
 A generally accepted criterion, is the Rayleigh criterion (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Rayleigh-criterion"

\end_inset

).
 According to this criterion two lines are considered to be resolved if
 the intensity at the saddle point is 
\begin_inset Formula $8/\pi^{2}$
\end_inset

 times the intensity at the two maxima.
 Therefore, at the saddle point (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2 beams intensity pattern"

\end_inset

), applying this criterion, we obtain that the maximum frequency separation
 between the two peaks before the Rayleigh criterion is no longer met is
 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\delta\omega & = & \omega-\omega^{'}\approx\frac{1.05\pi c}{Fnd\cos\theta},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we made the assumption that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta-\Delta^{'}$
\end_inset

 is small*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The 2 beams are of the same form 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{out}=\frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}+\frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta^{'}/2\right)},$
\end_inset

 so their saddle point will be at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Delta-\Delta^{'}\right)/2$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 between the 2 peaks.
 Hence, at the saddle point the intensity is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I_{out} & = & 2\frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\left(\Delta-\Delta^{'}\right)/4\right)}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

At what value of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 do we reach a maximum of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{out}$
\end_inset

? By symmetry, it is either at the saddle or somewhere else.
 But we are assuming a high reflectivity (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta,\Delta^{'}$
\end_inset

 is small) and so the maximum has to be at one of the peaks and we have
 that (say we pick the peak of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I_{out}/I_{0} & = & 1+\frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\left(\Delta-\Delta^{'}\right)/2\right)},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Delta-\Delta^{'}\right)$
\end_inset

 is because we set the origin at where the first beam is at a maximum and
 
\begin_inset Formula $sin^{2}x=sin^{2}-x$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 we shift the coordinates) so we want to find at what value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\omega=\omega-\omega^{'}$
\end_inset

, do we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{8}{\pi^{2}}\left(1+\frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\left(\Delta-\Delta^{'}\right)/2\right)}\right) & = & 2\frac{I_{0}}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\left(\Delta-\Delta^{'}\right)/4\right)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Using Mathematica (TODO) and again assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta-\Delta^{'}$
\end_inset

 is small, we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\omega=\omega-\omega^{'}=\frac{1.05\pi c}{Fnd\cos\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The resolving power is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
RP & = & \frac{\omega}{\delta\omega}\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{\omega Fnd\cos\theta}{1.05\pi c}.\label{eq:RP fabry perot}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

(Section 7.6.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vanDrielO"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Near resonance: Fabry-Perot as a damped harmonic oscillator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\xi & \equiv & \Delta-\Delta_{m}\\
 & = & \frac{2\left(\omega-\omega_{m}\right)nd\cos\theta}{c},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{m}=2m\pi$
\end_inset

 is the location of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

th transmission peak.
 By assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is small then we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
I/I_{0} & \approx & \frac{1}{1+\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\xi^{2}}.\label{eq:fabry perot near resonance}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I/I_{0} & = & \frac{1}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\Delta/2\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\left(\xi+\Delta_{m}\right)/2\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\xi/2+m\pi\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\xi/2\right)}\approx\frac{1}{1+4\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\xi^{2}/4}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

This is a Lorentzian with FWHM given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega=\pi c/Fnd\cos\theta$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A lorentzian has the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f & = & \frac{1}{\pi}\left(\frac{\gamma}{\left(x-x_{0}\right)^{2}+\gamma^{2}}\right),\\
 & = & 1/\pi\gamma\left(1+\left(\frac{x-x_{0}}{\gamma}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the location of the peak and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is HWHM (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lorentzian function"

\end_inset

).
 Now, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I/I_{0} & = & \frac{1}{1+\left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\xi^{2}}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{\pi}\frac{1}{1/\pi+F^{2}\xi^{2}/\pi^{3}}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{\pi}/\left(1/\pi+F^{2}\xi^{2}/\pi^{3}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{\pi}/\left(1/\pi+F^{2}\frac{4\left(\omega-\omega_{m}\right)^{2}n^{2}d^{2}\cos^{2}\theta}{c^{2}\pi^{3}}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{\pi}/\left(1/\pi+\left(\omega-\omega_{m}\right)^{2}/\left(\frac{c^{2}\pi^{3}}{4F^{2}n^{2}d^{2}\cos^{2}\theta}\right)\right)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{\pi}\times\left(\pi\right)/\left(1+\left(\omega-\omega_{m}\right)^{2}/\left(\frac{c^{2}\pi^{2}}{4F^{2}n^{2}d^{2}\cos^{2}\theta}\right)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\sqrt{\frac{c^{2}\pi^{2}}{4F^{2}n^{2}d^{2}\cos^{2}\theta}}$
\end_inset

 and FWHM=
\begin_inset Formula $2\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Note we dont need the exact form 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\pi\gamma\left(1+\left(\frac{x-x_{0}}{\gamma}\right)^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\pi\gamma$
\end_inset

 is just a constant and does not modify what the FWHM but only the height
 of the function
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and so the Fabry-Perot can be viewed as a macroscopic oscillator with a
 number of equally spaced resonance frequencies*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To see this connection, note that w
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
e have from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:near resonance forced damped SHO energy absorbed"

\end_inset

 that the energy absorbed by a forced damped harmonic oscillator is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I\left(\epsilon\right) & = & \frac{f^{2}\lambda}{4m\left(\epsilon^{2}+\lambda^{2}\right)},\\
 & = & \frac{\lambda f^{2}}{4m\lambda^{2}\left(\epsilon^{2}/\lambda^{2}+1\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{f^{2}}{4m\lambda}\frac{1}{\epsilon^{2}/\lambda^{2}+1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so we can associate 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{2}/4m\lambda$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

 and we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{1}{\lambda^{2}} & \equiv & \left(F/\pi\right)^{2}\\
\implies\lambda & \equiv & \frac{\pi}{F}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 These 'oscillators' have (by definition^
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The energy damping rate is defined to be the FWHM and the energy lifetime
 to be 1/(energy damping rate)
\end_layout

\end_inset

) energy damping rates given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega$
\end_inset

 and energy lifetimes of the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=1/\Delta\omega$
\end_inset

 and so the higher the finesse of the system the slower the rate of energy
 loss from the resonator is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(section 7.6.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vanDrielO"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

