\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

For a (typical) 10 cm separation of the mirrors with normally incident light
 the free spectral range corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{10}s^{-1}$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A wavelength is around 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-6}m$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
FSR & \approx & \frac{\pi\times3\times10^{8}}{10^{-1}}\\
 & \approx & 10^{9+1}=10^{10}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, which is much less than the frequency of visible light.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vanDrielO"

\end_inset

 section 7.6.2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Because the output of the interferometer is periodic as a function of frequency
 with period equal to the frequency of the spectral free range, the analysis
 of light sources with bandwidths greater than the spectral free range is
 at best complicated and one may be better off using a Michelson interferometer.
 The Fabry-Perot interferometer is most useful for analyzing light sources
 with a bandwidth less than the free spectral range.
 For such sources the typical output of the interferometer is given in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:fabry output multifrequency input"

\end_inset

.
 In this ﬁgure the variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 is achieved by scanning 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Although the output is still periodic in 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, the component frequency may be obtained by comparing the output with that
 of a true monochromatic source of known frequency^
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If we know what the frequency of one of the peaks in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:fabry output multifrequency input"

\end_inset

 then we can know the frequency of any other peak.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
