\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Rayleigh-criterion"

\end_inset

Rayleigh criterion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to say that we can resolve the lines in an intensity pattern we
 must adopt a suitable criterion.
 A generally accepted criterion, is the Rayleigh criterion.
 According to this criterion two lines are considered to be resolved if
 the intensity at the saddle point is 
\begin_inset Formula $8/\pi^{2}$
\end_inset

 times the intensity at the two maxima.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename intensity pattern 2 monochromatic lines.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:2 beams intensity pattern"

\end_inset

 (From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vanDrielO"

\end_inset

 section 7.6.2) Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 is a parameter that can be varied in a Fabry perot interferometer - see
 Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fabry parameter"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

